"# Chapter 15 — Grade 15: Multivariable & Linear Algebra

## Opening: Beyond One Variable

For most of human history, mathematics dealt with one thing changing at a time—a falling stone, a growing population, the curve of a single arc. But the world is richer than that. Temperature changes with both latitude *and* altitude. A business's profit depends on price *and* volume. The shape of a drumhead, the flow of air over a wing, the stresses in a bridge—all live in spaces where many variables dance together.

**Multivariable calculus** was born in the 18th century when mathematicians like Euler, Lagrange, and later Gauss realized that the machinery of calculus—limits, derivatives, integrals—could leap from the number line into the plane, into space, and beyond. At the same time, **linear algebra** emerged from the practical need to solve many equations in many unknowns: navigation, astronomy, surveying. By the 19th century, mathematicians like Cayley and Sylvester had abstracted the bookkeeping into matrices and vectors, objects that could be added, scaled, multiplied, and inverted—algebraic citizens in their own right.

**Uses in the world:** Every field that models reality in more than one dimension lives here. Engineers use gradients to find the steepest ascent on a hillside or the fastest cooling path in a metal casting. Economists maximize utility functions of many goods. Machine learning—at its heart—is linear algebra: matrices of weights, vectors of inputs, gradients descending toward a minimum loss. Computer graphics renders every frame by multiplying vectors and matrices that rotate, scale, and project a 3D world onto your screen.

**What we'll cover and why:** This chapter walks you from the plane into higher dimensions. We'll start with **vectors and matrices**—how to build them, add them, multiply them, and solve systems like *Ax* = *b*. Then we'll climb into **multivariable functions**—surfaces instead of curves—and learn to take **partial derivatives** (how a surface tilts in one direction) and **gradients** (the direction of steepest ascent). We'll close with a taste of **eigenvalues**, the hidden directions in which a matrix simply stretches or shrinks.

**Its utility in Motoi:** the canvas is a grid—rows and columns of dots, vectors of positions, colors as three-component tuples. When she wants to rotate a shape, she multiplies by a rotation matrix. When she's optimizing a path or a curve fit, she follows a gradient. When she's animating a flock or a physics sim, she's solving *F* = *ma* in vector form, dozens of particles at once, all represented as columns in a matrix. Multivariable calculus and linear algebra aren't abstract luxuries—they're the daily language of the dot-matrix world. We call it math, but we're really moving dots—now in formation, in space, obeying rules we can write down and compute.

Let's begin.

---

## Topic 1: Vectors—Arrows in Space

### History & Development

A **vector** started life in physics: a quantity with magnitude *and* direction—velocity, force, displacement. In the 19th century, the Irish mathematician William Rowan Hamilton tried to extend complex numbers to three dimensions and invented *quaternions*; around the same time, the American physicist J. Willard Gibbs and the British engineer Oliver Heaviside distilled the simpler \"vector calculus\" we use today—arrows you can add tip-to-tail and scale by numbers. By the early 20th century, vectors had become the universal language for anything that points: electric fields, gradients, velocities, momenta.

### Uses & Utility

Vectors represent *anything with direction*: the wind blowing northeast at 15 km/h, the force pulling a cart downhill, the displacement from one city to another. Physics is written in vectors; so is computer graphics (every pixel's color is a 3-vector), robotics (joint angles and velocities), and machine learning (every data point is a vector in feature space).

### What We'll Cover

We'll build vectors as lists of numbers, add and subtract them, scale them, measure their length (the *norm*), and compute the *dot product* (which measures how aligned two vectors are) and the *cross product* (which finds a vector perpendicular to both, in 3D). Every operation is exact—no floating-point surprises—and every example is a complete program you can run.

### Utility in the runtime's World

A dot on the canvas at *(x, y)* is a 2-vector. A color *(r, g, b)* is a 3-vector. When she moves a shape, she's adding a displacement vector to every point. When she measures how \"aligned\" two directions are (for shading, for collision detection), she takes a dot product. Vectors are the skeleton of the canvas.

---

### Example 1: Building a Vector

The simplest vector is a list of numbers. We use `(vec/make a b c ...)` to build one.

```scheme
(define v (vec/make 3 4))
v
```

<!-- BUILD: Runs and prints the vector (vec 3 4). -->

[VISUAL: Text output showing `(vec 3 4)` on the console/output pane.]

---

### Example 2: A 3D Vector

Vectors can have any dimension. Here's one in 3D space.

```scheme
(define w (vec/make 1 2 2))
w
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 1 2 2). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `(vec 1 2 2)`.]

---

### Example 3: Vector Addition

Add two vectors component-wise: *(a, b) + (c, d) = (a+c, b+d)*.

```scheme
(define u (vec/make 1 2))
(define v (vec/make 3 1))
(vec/+ u v)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 4 3). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `(vec 4 3)`. Optionally, a 2D Cartesian grid showing arrows from origin to (1,2), to (3,1), and their sum tip-to-tail to (4,3).]

---

### Example 4: Vector Subtraction

Subtract component-wise.

```scheme
(define u (vec/make 5 7))
(define v (vec/make 2 3))
(vec/- u v)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 3 4). -->

[VISUAL: Text output; optionally a diagram showing the displacement vector from v to u.]

---

### Example 5: Scaling a Vector

Multiply every component by a scalar.

```scheme
(define v (vec/make 1 2))
(vec/scale v 3)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 3 6). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `(vec 3 6)`. Arrow scaled 3× in the plane.]

---

### Example 6: The Zero Vector

The additive identity.

```scheme
(define z (vec/make 0 0 0))
(define w (vec/make 4 -1 2))
(vec/+ w z)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 4 -1 2), unchanged. -->

[VISUAL: Text output confirming w unchanged.]

---

### Example 7: Vector Norm (Length)

The *norm* is the Euclidean length: √(a² + b² + c²).

```scheme
(define v (vec/make 3 4))
(vec/norm v)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints 5.000 (since 3² + 4² = 25). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `5.000`.]

---

### Example 8: Normalizing a Vector

A *unit vector* has norm 1. Divide by the norm.

```scheme
(define v (vec/make 3 4))
(vec/normalize v)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 0.600 0.800), since 3/5 and 4/5. -->

[VISUAL: Text output `(vec 0.600 0.800)`. Arrow of length 1 in the same direction.]

---

### Example 9: Dot Product

The dot product measures alignment: *u* · *v* = Σ(uᵢ vᵢ).

```scheme
(define u (vec/make 1 0))
(define v (vec/make 0 1))
(vec/dot u v)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints 0 (perpendicular vectors). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `0`. Two perpendicular arrows on a grid.]

---

### Example 10: Dot Product of Parallel Vectors

```scheme
(define u (vec/make 2 3))
(define v (vec/make 4 6))
(vec/dot u v)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints 26 (2×4 + 3×6 = 8 + 18 = 26). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `26`.]

---

### Example 11: Angle Between Vectors

cos(θ) = (*u* · *v*) / (‖*u*‖ ‖*v*‖).

```scheme
(define u (vec/make 1 0))
(define v (vec/make 1 1))
(vec/angle-between u v)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints 45.000 degrees (or π/4 radians if your verb returns radians; adjust). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `45.000°`. Two arrows at 45° on a grid.]

---

### Example 12: Cross Product in 3D

The cross product *u* × *v* yields a vector perpendicular to both (right-hand rule).

```scheme
(define u (vec/make 1 0 0))
(define v (vec/make 0 1 0))
(vec/cross u v)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 0 0 1), the z-axis. -->

[VISUAL: 3D diagram (or text output) showing x, y, z axes and the resulting vector pointing up.]

---

### Example 13: Cross Product Magnitude

The magnitude ‖*u* × *v*‖ = ‖*u*‖ ‖*v*‖ sin(θ), the area of the parallelogram.

```scheme
(define u (vec/make 3 0 0))
(define v (vec/make 0 4 0))
(define w (vec/cross u v))
(vec/norm w)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints 12.000 (3 × 4 × sin(90°) = 12). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `12.000`.]

---

### Example 14: Projection of One Vector onto Another

Project *u* onto *v*: proj = ((*u* · *v̂*) *v̂*), where *v̂* is the unit vector of *v*.

```scheme
(define u (vec/make 3 4))
(define v (vec/make 1 0))
(define v-hat (vec/normalize v))
(define proj-length (vec/dot u v-hat))
(vec/scale v-hat proj-length)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 3.000 0.000), the shadow of u on the x-axis. -->

[VISUAL: 2D grid showing u as an arrow, v along x-axis, and the perpendicular drop to the projection point.]

---

### Example 15: A Simple Physics Step—Velocity Vector

An object at *(10, 20)* with velocity *(2, -1)* moves in one time step.

```scheme
(define pos (vec/make 10 20))
(define vel (vec/make 2 -1))
(define new-pos (vec/+ pos vel))
new-pos
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 12 19). -->

[VISUAL: 2D grid showing two dots: old position and new position, with an arrow (the velocity) connecting them.]

