## Topic 3: Solving Linear Systems—The Heart of Linear Algebra

### History & Development

Solving *Ax* = *b* (a system of linear equations) is one of the oldest problems in mathematics. Gaussian elimination—systematically zeroing out entries below the diagonal—was used by Chinese mathematicians in 200 BCE and rediscovered by Carl Friedrich Gauss in the 19th century. Today it's the workhorse algorithm for solving systems, inverting matrices, and computing ranks.

### Uses & Utility

Every time you fit a line to data (least squares), balance chemical equations, find currents in an electrical circuit, or solve for forces in a truss, you're solving *Ax* = *b*. Engineering, economics, physics, statistics—all lean on this.

### What We'll Cover

We'll set up systems as matrices, solve them with `linalg/solve`, and check the solutions. We'll see cases with unique solutions, no solution (inconsistent), and infinitely many (underdetermined).

### Utility in the runtime's World

When the runtime needs three lines to meet at a point (say, the corners of a triangle given constraints), she's solving a 3×3 system. When she's fitting a curve to data points, she's solving a least-squares matrix equation. The canvas may be dots, but the math underneath is linear algebra.

---

### Example 28: Solve a 2×2 System

*x* + 2*y* = 5, 3*x* + 4*y* = 11.

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 1 2)
                             (list 3 4))))
(define b (vec/make 5 11))
(linalg/solve A b)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 1.000 2.000), the solution (x=1, y=2). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `(vec 1.000 2.000)`. Optionally, a 2D plot of two lines intersecting at (1,2).]

---

### Example 29: Verify the Solution

Multiply *A* by the solution vector; should yield *b*.

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 1 2)
                             (list 3 4))))
(define b (vec/make 5 11))
(define x (linalg/solve A b))
;; Convert x to column, multiply
(define x-col (matrix/make (list (list (vec/ref x 0))
                                  (list (vec/ref x 1)))))
(matrix/* A x-col)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints ((5)(11)), confirming A x = b. -->

[VISUAL: Text output ((5)(11)).]

---

### Example 30: Solve a 3×3 System

*x* + *y* + *z* = 6, 2*x* + 3*y* + *z* = 14, *x* + *y* + 2*z* = 9.

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 1 1 1)
                             (list 2 3 1)
                             (list 1 1 2))))
(define b (vec/make 6 14 9))
(linalg/solve A b)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 1.000 2.000 3.000), the solution (x=1, y=2, z=3). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `(vec 1.000 2.000 3.000)`.]

---

### Example 31: A Singular System (No Unique Solution)

If det(*A*) = 0, the system is either inconsistent or has infinitely many solutions.

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 1 2)
                             (list 2 4))))
(define b (vec/make 3 6))
(linalg/solve A b)
```

<!-- BUILD: May return 'nan or (escalate 'singular ...), depending on implementation. -->

[VISUAL: Text output showing the honest-null result (escalate 'singular ...) or 'nan.]

---

### Example 32: Rank of a Matrix

The rank is the number of linearly independent rows (or columns).

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 1 2 3)
                             (list 2 4 6)
                             (list 1 1 1))))
(linalg/rank A)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints 2 (row 2 is a multiple of row 1, so only 2 independent rows). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `2`.]

---

### Example 33: Trace of a Matrix

The trace is the sum of the diagonal entries.

```scheme
(define A (matrix/make (list (list 1 2 3)
                             (list 4 5 6)
                             (list 7 8 9))))
(linalg/trace A)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints 15 (1 + 5 + 9). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `15`.]

---

## Topic 4: Multivariable Functions—Surfaces, Not Curves

### History & Development

Once calculus conquered the single-variable world, mathematicians asked: what if *f* depends on *x* and *y*? The answers came in the 18th century—Euler, Lagrange, and others extended limits, derivatives, and integrals to functions of several variables. The *partial derivative* ∂*f*/∂*x* (hold *y* fixed, differentiate with respect to *x*) became the new atom. The *gradient* ∇*f* bundled all the partials into a vector pointing uphill. By the 19th century, multivariable calculus was the language of physics (heat, fluids, electromagnetism) and remains so today.

### Uses & Utility

Any quantity depending on multiple inputs is a multivariable function. Elevation on a map: *h*(*x*, *y*). Temperature in a room: *T*(*x*, *y*, *z*, *t*). Profit as a function of price and quantity. Machine learning loss functions depend on thousands of parameters. Multivariable calculus finds maxima, minima, and the direction to move to improve a function.

### What We'll Cover

We'll define functions of two or more variables, compute partial derivatives (the slope in one direction), assemble the gradient (a vector of all partials), and visualize gradient fields—the landscape of steepest ascent.

### Utility in the runtime's World

the canvas is a function *f*(*x*, *y*) → color (or height, or intensity). When she wants to find the brightest spot, she follows the gradient. When she's shading a surface, she computes the normal (perpendicular to the gradient). When she's optimizing a layout or a fit, she's doing gradient descent—following ∇*f* downhill.

---

### Example 34: A Simple Two-Variable Function

*f*(*x*, *y*) = *x*² + *y*².

```scheme
(define (f x y)
  (+ (* x x) (* y y)))

(f 3 4)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints 25 (9 + 16). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `25`. Optionally, a 3D surface plot or contour plot of f(x,y) = x² + y² (a paraboloid).]

---

### Example 35: Evaluate at Several Points

```scheme
(define (f x y)
  (+ (* x x) (* y y)))

(list (f 0 0) (f 1 0) (f 0 1) (f 1 1))
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (0 1 1 2). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `(0 1 1 2)`. A scatter plot of these points on a 3D surface.]

---

### Example 36: Partial Derivative ∂f/∂x

For *f*(*x*, *y*) = *x*² + *y*², ∂*f*/∂*x* = 2*x*. We can compute it numerically or symbolically; here we'll define it.

```scheme
(define (f x y)
  (+ (* x x) (* y y)))

(define (df-dx x y)
  (* 2 x))

(df-dx 3 4)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints 6. -->

[VISUAL: Text output `6`.]

---

### Example 37: Partial Derivative ∂f/∂y

∂*f*/∂*y* = 2*y*.

```scheme
(define (f x y)
  (+ (* x x) (* y y)))

(define (df-dy x y)
  (* 2 y))

(df-dy 3 4)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints 8. -->

[VISUAL: Text output `8`.]

---

### Example 38: The Gradient Vector ∇f

∇*f* = (∂*f*/∂*x*, ∂*f*/∂*y*).

```scheme
(define (f x y)
  (+ (* x x) (* y y)))

(define (grad-f x y)
  (vec/make (* 2 x) (* 2 y)))

(grad-f 3 4)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 6 8). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `(vec 6 8)`. An arrow at (3,4) pointing in the direction (6,8) on a contour plot of f.]

---

### Example 39: Gradient Points Uphill

The gradient points in the direction of steepest ascent. At any point, if you move in the direction ∇*f*, *f* increases fastest.

```scheme
(define (f x y)
  (+ (* x x) (* y y)))

(define (grad-f x y)
  (vec/make (* 2 x) (* 2 y)))

;; At the origin, gradient is zero (a minimum)
(grad-f 0 0)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 0 0). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `(vec 0 0)`. A contour plot with concentric circles around the origin, gradient vectors radiating outward except at the origin where it's zero.]

---

### Example 40: A Saddle Function

*f*(*x*, *y*) = *x*² − *y*² (a saddle).

```scheme
(define (f x y)
  (- (* x x) (* y y)))

(f 1 1)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints 0. -->

[VISUAL: A 3D saddle surface plot: rises along x, falls along y.]

---

### Example 41: Gradient of the Saddle

∇*f* = (2*x*, −2*y*).

```scheme
(define (f x y)
  (- (* x x) (* y y)))

(define (grad-f x y)
  (vec/make (* 2 x) (* -2 y)))

(grad-f 1 1)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 2 -2). -->

[VISUAL: Text output `(vec 2 -2)`. An arrow at (1,1) pointing toward (2,-2) direction on a contour plot.]

---

### Example 42: Gradient Field on a Grid

Plot the gradient at several points.

```scheme
(define (f x y)
  (+ (* x x) (* y y)))

(define (grad-f x y)
  (vec/make (* 2 x) (* 2 y)))

(define points
  (list (list -1 -1) (list 0 -1) (list 1 -1)
        (list -1  0) (list 0  0) (list 1  0)
        (list -1  1) (list 0  1) (list 1  1)))

(define gradients
  (map (lambda (pt)
         (grad-f (car pt) (cadr pt)))
       points))

gradients
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints a list of 9 gradient vectors. -->

[VISUAL: A 2D vector field plot: at each of the 9 grid points, draw an arrow in the direction of the gradient. The arrows radiate outward from the origin.]

We can render this with `plot/vector-field`:

```scheme
(define (f x y)
  (+ (* x x) (* y y)))

(define (grad-f-x x y) (* 2 x))
(define (grad-f-y x y) (* 2 y))

(plot/vector-field grad-f-x grad-f-y -2 2 -2 2)
```

<!-- BUILD: Returns a plot a-list (type vector-field ...) that renders a grid of arrows. -->

[VISUAL: A Cartesian grid from -2 to 2 in x and y, with arrows at grid points showing the gradient direction and magnitude (longer arrows farther from origin).]

---

### Example 43: Directional Derivative

The rate of change of *f* in the direction of a unit vector *u* is ∇*f* · *u*.

```scheme
(define (f x y)
  (+ (* x x) (* y y)))

(define (grad-f x y)
  (vec/make (* 2 x) (* 2 y)))

(define grad-at-point (grad-f 1 1)) ;; (vec 2 2)
(define direction (vec/normalize (vec/make 1 0))) ;; unit vector along x

(vec/dot grad-at-point direction)
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints 2, the rate of increase of f at (1,1) in the x-direction. -->

[VISUAL: Text output `2`.]

