### Example 46: Gradient Perpendicular to Level Curves

The gradient ∇*f* at any point is perpendicular to the level curve through that point.

```scheme
(define (f x y)
  (+ (* x x) (* y y)))

(define (grad-f x y)
  (vec/make (* 2 x) (* 2 y)))

;; At (1, √3) on the circle x² + y² = 4, the gradient is (2, 2√3), perpendicular to the tangent.
(define grad-at-point (grad-f 1 1.732))
grad-at-point
```

<!-- BUILD: Prints (vec 2.000 3.464). -->

[VISUAL: Text output. A plot showing the circle, the point (1, √3), and the gradient arrow pointing radially outward (perpendicular to the circle).]

